WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.480
So this is going to be a two-hour discussion, but in seven minutes.

00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:07.820
So optimization of haplotransplant, 2026 perspective.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:10.000
No disclosures.

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:13.840
This is the overview of what we will discuss.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:18.220
Optimization mainly through donor selection, as well as other factors.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:22.900
So when we're selecting a donor, there are so many factors to consider.

00:00:23.180 --> 00:00:25.020
Obviously, not all of them are equal.

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:30.240
So the question is, which ones of these factors are actually important that we should prioritize?

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:36.840
When we look at the NMDP guidelines for selecting haplotransplants, there isn't really much

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:37.880
to guide the process.

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:42.140
However, they do say to avoid DSA, I don't think there's any ambiguity about this.

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:47.620
They do say select a younger donor, specifically younger than 31 years.

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:48.740
We'll talk more about that.

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:54.100
They do also suggest that there are certain HLA factors that we should be considering.

00:00:55.020 --> 00:01:02.600
So donor age from the very first seminal study in 2001 had been shown to be associated with survival.

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:12.000
Since 2001 to now, there has been a tremendous amount of studies that showed us that there is an association with survival.

00:01:12.260 --> 00:01:15.700
So much so that it is now part of the guidelines for donors.

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:23.160
However, as you can see, there is multiple variations to what is the exact age that we should be selecting for our donors.

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:25.000
Now, the problem with this is that we don't have an exact age.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.400
The problem with this is that when you're thinking about saying a donor is either young or old,

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:31.780
you're essentially putting the donors in two different buckets.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.700
In every group, you're assuming that everyone has the same risk factors.

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:42.880
So we're saying a 31-year-old is similar to a 65-year-old donor, and that just biologically doesn't make sense.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.860
When we looked at donor age in a recent era and we used conditional methods,

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:54.120
we saw that there is no association between donor age and overall survival.

00:01:54.980 --> 00:02:22.820
So we saw that the relationship between donor age and survival was rather non-linear.

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:24.900
So you can see that the optimal age of a donor is not linear.

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:24.960
So we saw that the relationship between donor age and survival is rather non-linear.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.360
The ideal age for donors is somewhere between 20 to mid-40s.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:34.420
So there is more flexibility than what we think when we come up with these arbitrary age cutoffs.

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:39.840
And what that gives you also is the opportunity to consider other factors for selection of donors.

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:45.800
We know that donor age is influenced by multiple factors, including patient's age,

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.500
as well as conditioning regimen intensity.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:54.860
When we used machine learning models to look at the interaction between patient age,

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:59.240
and donor age, we found that there is a significant synergistic effect

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.760
where you have the worst survival when you pair an older patient with an older donor,

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:08.500
as you can see here in this heat map with the yellow corner.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:14.280
The best outcomes in the lower risk of mortality were associated with younger patients

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:18.560
who are paired with a donor that's somewhere between 20 to mid-40s.

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:21.820
Again, it shows you that donor age is not an independent factor,

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:24.760
but rather it's modulated by multiple factors,

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:25.940
including patient age.

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:30.760
So this foundational study showed us that in terms of HLA,

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:36.060
there is a specific favorable HLA profile that we should be or recommended for us to follow.

00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:42.720
This is a B-liter match, DQ match, DR mismatch, and DPB1 non-permissive mismatch.

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:47.740
When we looked at recent era of transplant, again, using machine learning models,

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:54.320
we found that the non-permissive, the DPB1 non-permissive mismatch is actually associated with worse survival.

00:03:54.900 --> 00:04:00.800
However, B-liter and DQ match continued to show survival benefits.

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:06.400
We also were able to rank these HLA so we can choose which ones are more important than others.

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:13.540
And with this, we have a suggested favorable HLA profile, which is DPB1 avoidance of non-permissive mismatch,

00:04:13.540 --> 00:04:16.340
but continue to look for B-liter and DQ matches.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:19.860
So how can you put all of this together?

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:24.720
We came up with a prediction of a predictive model that,

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.360
we stratified our patients into four different quartiles,

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:31.960
and this is based on their three-year overall survival.

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:39.760
And if you do use the best donor case based on these HLA markers and the donor age range from 20 to early 40s,

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:45.040
you're actually able to improve the prediction of your patient's survival.

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:51.840
So for instance, patients in the orange here in the third quartile, they have a prediction of 20% at three years,

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.560
and you're able to improve that up to 50%.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:05:01.220
Patients who have the worst outcome at 10% were actually able to improve up to 30%.

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:08.340
So donor selection can actually improve your predicted survival of patients when you're using a donor, a haplodonor.

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:15.980
Other factors that may not be as considered when we're looking at selection.

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.740
So bone marrow have been associated with lower GVHD.

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.740
However, it hasn't changed our practice much.

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:24.840
We know that peripheral blood continues to be the,

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.340
most commonly used and generally as we talked,

00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:33.040
donor age seems to be always more considered than other factors.

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:37.280
We saw that with peripheral blood and female donors,

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:43.400
the risk of chronic GVHD is much higher than if you choose an older donor.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:44.240
So you can see here,

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:47.720
if you go from an 18-year-old to a 50-year-old donor,

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:54.280
using a bone marrow male graft has a risk factor of 27% with chronic GVH,

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:54.820
which is still,

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:59.300
still lower than using an 18-year-old female peripheral blood graft.

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.620
So it is important to consider other factors,

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:04.560
knowing that we have the flexibility.

00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:06.420
Conditioning regimen,

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:09.700
probably one of the most controversial topic in transplant.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:12.840
Now we know that it is influenced by multiple factors,

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:16.140
including donor type, patient age.

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:21.760
We did not find that myeloablation provide any survival outcomes,

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:24.800
survival benefits in AML, MDS, and AMC.

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:27.600
MPN, irrespective of age.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.600
Surprisingly, we did find that in ALL,

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:36.380
reduced intensity flucide TBI was associated with superior outcomes in terms of survival,

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:39.000
similar relapse in lower NRM.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.480
This is still a work in progress.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:44.040
However, we did share this in EBMT just a couple of weeks ago,

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:50.920
but it is important to emphasize that myeloablation is not always the answer.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:54.780
We know that a third of our patients don't have matched donors,

00:06:54.780 --> 00:06:58.620
and with the donor selection prognosis score,

00:06:58.620 --> 00:07:05.440
we know now that we're able to predict which of these donors are less likely to have an unrelated matched donor,

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:08.800
which allows us to move to transplant without delays.

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:17.400
And the BMT CT on 1702 showed us that the overall survival is similar between those patients.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:23.880
We also know that a second and a third degree haploid donors have the same outcomes as a first degree.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:24.760
So expanding

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:28.280
the search and moving early is important.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:29.240
Future directions.

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:34.140
We are using machine learning models to personalize donor selection,

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:39.980
where you can use these calculators and input all of the complex factors.

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:43.320
This is led by Ritesh Mehta in our department.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:48.720
And in conclusion, donor selection can improve your predicted survival of your patients.

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:54.740
We know that HLA factors are important and should be considered for survival, patient age and disease risk,

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:58.720
are more dominant factors, more so than donor age.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.400
We should be avoiding older haploid donors.

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:05.180
If you have an older patient, maybe you can expand beyond the first degree.

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:07.240
Consider grandchildren.

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:11.360
Haploid donor search should be done early and upfront without delays.

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:17.180
We know that arbitrary age cutoffs can be misleading and we know that age is actually flexible,

00:08:17.180 --> 00:08:24.720
which allows you to consider other factors such as a male donor and bone marrow and myeloablation is

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:28.160
not always the answer. And with that, I thank you for your attention.
